snippet.textDisplay:
A mixed bag. It is awesome that a company actually wants to do somethinng about child abuse but it really seems like an justification to get more data from customers. If the system is not abused and officialy regulated, this would be amazing.
When it comes to making people saver, especially online, I wish the internet would finally get more transparent. I think it would be amazing if everybody would be completely anonymous online as long as they just consume content. But when people start to affect others by e.g uploading stuff, commenting etc, everybody about them regarding the data they uploaded should be public. People should be able to see who wrote a certain comment, who they are, where they life and how to contact them. People could be made responsible for the harm they create and also for the good they do. In RL, people aren't anonymous when they affect others too. It would save so many lifes by preventing bullying. And regarding the ammount of pubblic data, it would also prevent others from abusing it. But that is another topic and I already know people would cry about it for no reason, because they can't imagine having to take responsibilities for their own actions.

snippet.textDisplay:
The apple thing does not surprise me. The USA gov't must have some leverage or favor on Mr. Cook, the board or Apple's plans.  The US Gov't "theoretically" is restrained by the law, and due process. It is known the gov't often asks private entities who are not under such restraint and can "weather" lawsuits to do "favors" for the government. It's a known secret that the USA's "national security/law enforcement/intelligence community" regularly asks the USA's allies (UK) to look at data that has been collected and send back the results.  

Another example of this was Bestbuy's Geek Squad was unbeknownst to consumers actively working with Law Enforcement via their bounty program.  The whole Bestbuy thing could have been avoided by not actively participating, as it incentivized the planting of evidence for money. Simply posting a sign and a blurb on the service contract that says: "If we find illegal material as defined under USA law it will be reported to law enforcement with or without your consent." I inform my patrons orally and in writing before I even look at their machines.

Using the "Save the Children or think about the children" argument is an emotional argument and a way to make people feel good about not thinking about the consequences. I recall when "for the children" was the justification in the 1990s when Federal Law Enforcement in Waco TX, wanted to use a tank, and burned said children alive*.  "for the children".  I am all for getting rid of child Frackers, but do it correctly and leaglly so they can be put away instead of walk free on technicalities and due process violations. 

*Even if law enforcement didn't start the fire, their behavior and handling of the situation was a big contributor to a fire being started as most cult leaders never want to die alone.
